<span class="headline">APRS Variable Replacement Script</span>
<p/>

This script is available for anybody who wants to design their own simple
web page and embed the latest APRS packet data for a specific station.
<p />

You just design your own HTML page, paste the desired variables wherever you
want them to appear on the page, and then pass your page's URL to
this script, along with the callsign of the station.
<p />

For instance, I've created a page in my personal space on another server:
<p />

<a href="http://www.warn.org/n8qq/aprs.html" target="_blank"
>http://www.warn.org/n8qq/aprs.html</a>
<p />

You can see the <a href="./index.cgi?varlist=1">variables</a>
that appear in the page, such as "$call" and "$lat".
Those variables will be replaced with the actual data from the most recent
packet of the specified station...
<p />

Here is the same page when passed through this variable replacement script:
<p />

<a href="./index.cgi?call=N8QQ&url=www.warn.org/n8qq/aprs.html" target="_blank">
http://aprs.n8qq.com/replace/index.cgi?call=<font color="#c00000">N8QQ</font>&url=<font color="#c00000">www.warn.org/n8qq/aprs.html</font></a>
<p />

Just put your callsign and your web page's URL in place of mine (shown in red), and that's all there is to it.
Putting "http://" on the front of your URL is optional, and it will be assumed
if not included, as demonstrated in the URL above.  (meaning that you should be able to use any protocol
that you can access via URL)
<p />

<a href="./index.cgi?varlist=1">Check here</a> to view a list of all
possible variables.  You can use this list to copy and paste them into your HTML page.
<p />

If you have ideas for added functionality to this script, please <a href="mailto:brad@n8qq.com">let me know</a>.
I'll add whatever I can as time allows.
